### Function Parameters

Parameters are variables that receive values passed into a function. C++ supports several parameter passing mechanisms.

---

### Pass by Value

A copy of the argument is made. Changes inside the function do not affect the original:

```cpp
void increment(int x) {
  x++;  // Only modifies local copy
}

int main() {
  int a = 5;
  increment(a);
  cout << a;  // Still 5
}
```

---

### Pass by Reference

The function receives a reference to the original variable. Changes affect the original:

```cpp
void increment(int& x) {
  x++;  // Modifies original
}

int a = 5;
increment(a);
cout << a;  // 6
```

---

### Pass by Const Reference

Efficient for large objects without allowing modification:

```cpp
void display(const vector<int>& data) {
  for (int x : data) {
    cout << x << " ";
  }
  // data.push_back(5);  // ERROR: const prevents modification
}
```

---

### Pass by Pointer

Similar to reference, but can accept `nullptr`:

```cpp
void setValue(int* ptr, int value) {
  if (ptr) {         // Check for nullptr
    *ptr = value;
  }
}
```

---

### Parameter Passing Guide

| Type | Use When |
|------|----------|
| By value | Small objects, no modification needed |
| By reference | Modification needed |
| Const reference | Large objects, read-only |
| Pointer | Optional parameter or C-compatible API |

---

> **Key Point:** Use pass by reference (`&`) to modify the original argument. Use pass by const reference (`const &`) for large objects that should not be modified. Use pass by value for small, trivial types.

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

void swap(int& a, int& b) {
  int temp = a;
  a = b;
  b = temp;
}

int main() {
  int x = 10, y = 20;
  cout << "Before: " << x << " " << y << endl;
  swap(x, y);
  cout << "After: " << x << " " << y << endl;
  return 0;
}
